{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \H4, fourth-best from your longest suit — the normal start against 6NT.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 6NT with a 25-point rock: count eleven top tricks, twelve needed. This lesson is about the squeeze's ignition switch — RECTIFYING THE COUNT — and this hand teaches it in its purest form: the trick you must lose should be lost at TRICK ONE. Duck the opening lead. It costs nothing you were keeping, and from that instant the defenders can never win another trick — which is exactly the condition every squeeze requires.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West leads a low heart: play LOW from dummy, low from hand — East's ten wins trick one, and your count is rectified before you have won a trick. Win the heart return, and now simply run everything black: four spades, four clubs. East must keep his heart king honest against dummy's queen, so his diamonds go — the jack flutters away, and when you cash the ace the queen comes down with it. Your \D9 wins trick thirteen. Twelve tricks.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The whole slam was decided at trick one, by the trick you LOST. Duck immediately, and the squeeze runs itself; win trick one instead, and East always has a safe card to spare at the end. Rectify first — the earlier the concession, the longer the pressure has to work. That is the habit this lesson wants you to build: count your tricks, and give away the loser while it is cheapest.}
