{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \SJ, top of your \SJ-T sequence — the safe start against the notrump slam.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Another huge hand, another 6NT, and this time the flaw is concrete: your diamond suit — A-8-6-4-3 opposite K-T-5 — must lose a trick to East's guarded honors no matter how you play it. The rectify-the-count discipline says: if a trick MUST be lost, lose it NOW, not later. Concede the diamond at trick two, while every other suit is still under lock, and let the run do the rest.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] Win the spade lead and immediately play a LOW diamond from both hands — East wins cheaply, blinking. That was the only trick the defense will ever take. Win the return, cash your hearts and black winners, and watch East's hand fall apart: he must guard clubs against your ace-king-jack leftovers and diamonds against dummy's king-ten, and he cannot. The jack goes, the ace fells his queen, and the humble \D8 wins trick thirteen.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The concession at trick two looked eccentric and was actually the safest play on the board: the diamond loser existed in every line, and only its TIMING was yours to choose. Lose it early and East spends the whole hand being squeezed; lose it late and he escapes. Same trick, different moment, opposite result — that is what rectifying the count means.}
