{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \S5, fourth-best from your longest suit — the quiet start against 6NT.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Gerber found three aces and you sit in 6NT needing twelve. The count: eleven on top once the diamonds behave. One short — and at the slam level the rectifying duck takes nerve, because the trick you must give away is in your BEST suit. Dummy's clubs are A-K-T-5-3 over your J-4; the queen is out. Plan to lead the JACK and, when the queen covers, let it HOLD — dummy's ace-ten stay poised, the count is rectified, and the run does the rest.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] Win the spade lead in hand. Cash one top club, then the moment of discipline: lead the \CJ and DUCK when East produces the queen — dummy's A-T sitting over the suit, untouched. East exits; win, and now run everything: diamonds, spades, the club ace and ten. West, guarding spades and hearts and the club length all at once, is ground to powder — and dummy's FIVE of clubs wins trick twelve. Twelve tricks, losing only the trick you chose to lose.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Ducking with ace-ten OVER the queen — giving a trick to the one card you were entitled to capture — is the most counterintuitive play on this shelf, and it was worth the slam. Once the count was rectified there was no defense: the run squeezed West flat and the five of clubs collected. The better your suit, the harder the duck feels, and the more it pays. Trick one, trick two, trick five — the first three boards of this lesson in one sentence: the sooner you can afford to lose it, the sooner you should.}
[Note "1:Gerber"]
[Note "2:A=3 out of 4"]
