{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \C8, top of your doubleton — partner doubled Stayman to ask for a club lead, and you oblige.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 3NT needing nine tricks, and East's double of 2\C has drawn you a map: the club honors, and most of the missing strength, sit on your right. Count winners: two hearts, three spades with the finesse the double has marked, three diamonds — and there is the rub. With Q-T-9-7 of diamonds behind your eight, the suit owes the defense one trick in every line. You can afford four losers in all. The rectify discipline at game level: schedule every loser EARLY, and let the endgame close around West.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] Dummy's singleton king falls under East's ace at trick one — the double told you everything and won them nothing extra. Win the heart return, and pay the diamond debt at once: low from both hands, and East's singleton JACK wins the trick. Take the next heart, pick up the spades — the jack rides through the doubler and holds — then hand East his clubs: jack and queen score, but your TEN is now the fourth-round boss. Win his exit, and dummy's spade king is the squeeze card: West must keep the heart queen over dummy's jack and both diamonds over your eight — three cards, two jobs. The diamond ten leaves his hand; your ace swallows his queen; and the EIGHT of diamonds wins trick thirteen.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Four losers, all paid by trick ten — a club at once, the diamond the suit owed at trick three, two clubs when YOU chose — and after that the defense never won again. Rectifying the count is not slam furniture; it is bookkeeping, and it works at 3NT for nine tricks exactly as it works at 6NT for twelve. Notice what the duck protected: from the moment you conceded the third trick, your eight of diamonds was a menace, and West spent the rest of the hand dying in front of it.}
[Note "1:Stayman"]
