{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \DJ, top of your J-T sequence — solid and safe against the notrump slam, even through the opener's suit.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Partner invited seven and you settled in 6NT: twelve tricks. Count them — three spades, two hearts, three diamonds, three clubs — eleven, and the twelfth is nowhere honest. So the squeeze checklist: the heart suit, your 8-6 opposite K-5-4-2, owes the defense its third round no matter what. Rectify by paying it EARLY — and note the refinement on this board: the duck also keeps the heart ACE in your hand, and that ace, cashed at the right moment, will be the squeeze card itself.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] Take the diamond lead with the queen and start shaping the ending: a club to the TEN — a free finesse through West that strips his guard down to queen-eight — then the king, the diamond king, a spade to your king. Now the debt: lead a low heart and duck in dummy — East wins the SEVEN, the cheapest trick a defense ever bought, and exactly the one you owed. Win the diamond return, cross in hearts to the king, cash both top spades ending in dummy, queen gathering West's jack. Then the heart ace — and West is broken: he must keep the diamond ten over your eight, so his club eight goes; the jack forces his queen under dummy's ace; and dummy's FOUR of clubs wins trick thirteen.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Board one ducked at trick one, board two at trick two — here the duck waited until trick six, because it had a second job: the heart ace had to survive until the moment the run had tightened, and the duck is what kept a heart in your hand to reach it. WHEN you rectify is set by the squeeze's needs, not by habit — the rule is before the pressure card, not always immediately. And give trick two its due: the club ten was preparation, not greed; it shaved West's guard so thin that one discard at the end finished him.}
