{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \H4, fourth-best from your longest suit — the standard start against 6NT.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Fourth suit forcing found no fit and partner drove to 6NT on raw power. The lead is already a gift — your ten will score at trick one — bringing the count to eleven: four spades, four hearts, the diamond ace, two top clubs. For the twelfth, look at your club spots: A-5-4-2 opposite K-9-6, with East's jack-ten-eight lurking. The suit owes him a trick — pay it at once, cheaply, while every other suit is sealed. And do not despair of your diamonds: dummy's ace is singleton, so your queen-jack-ten will never win a TRICK — but a threat does not need to win tricks to do its work.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] The four rides to your TEN. Club to the king, and now the discipline: dummy's six, East's eight — play the FOUR, holding the ace. West's queen wins: the count is rectified at trick three. Dummy's stiff ace takes the diamond return, and the run begins: four spades, overtaking your king; the heart queen; the top hearts. Under the pressure your own hand sheds its dead diamonds one by one — but the QUEEN stays till the end, standing guard duty as a threat against East's king. On dummy's last winner, the heart ace, East holds the diamond king, the club jack and the club ten: three cards, two jobs. Watch what leaves. As played the ten goes — so keep the club five: the ace fells his jack, and the FIVE wins trick thirteen. Had the diamond KING gone instead, you throw the club five and your shadow queen takes the last trick.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Two lessons in one ending. First, the familiar arithmetic: a trick that must be lost was lost at trick three, and the defense never scored again. Second, the new skill: a squeeze does not always announce WHICH menace will ripen. Your last discard depended on East's — the club five and the diamond queen were interchangeable until his card hit the table. Rectify early, run everything, and hold your own endgame loose until the defender commits. The concession buys the ending; the watching cashes it.}
[Note "1:Fourth suit game force"]
